The resurgence of communism in Russia
Moscow—More than a year ago, during a sabbatical from the American university where I was teaching, I returned to my hometown of Moscow.
My destination was not a bastion of free speech.
But some freedoms still remained in this place.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny once traveled across the country in an attempt to gain the support of politicians not controlled by the Kremlin.
Protests erupted among the populace.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts are not necessarily following the Kremlin's line.
The Communist Party is widely seen as a relic of the past.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and the protests he initiated have been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was outlawed as "extremist," and its members are facing exile or investigation.
Almost every day, journalists, media outlets, human rights advocates, or independent organizations are added to the "foreign agents" list — or even worse — labeled as "unwanted."
Over the past year, Russia has slipped into a non-free state, a situation not distant but very intense.
For example, in 2012, a law was enacted to designate foreign agents, aiming to undermine or discredit organizations or individuals engaged in "political activities" while simultaneously receiving funding from abroad.
But the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point that simply sharing a tweet is now a reason for being labeled a foreign agent.
The "unwanted" label can lead to your complete prohibition.
) This year alone, the foreign agents list saw a record increase of 101 entities.
The total of 359 includes 88 media-related organizations and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the above-mentioned "agents" must be listed because they "influence national politics."
But of course, the core objective of news and propaganda work is to influence politics.
And this is precisely the problem: although President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics in the foreseeable future, he views criticism as a threat to his survival.
Despite enduring all this silence and persecution, the only real opposition group that has survived and remains within the Kremlin is the Communist Party, an unlikely group.
This is largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy — that is, urging people to support forces most likely to defeat candidates backed by the Kremlin — and the Communist Party performed very strongly in last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data show that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the State Duma (parliament) votes, while the Kremlin-backed United Russia party received nearly 49.8%.
But the Communists refused to acknowledge the result, insisting that the vote had been rigged.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have received about 30% of the votes, while the United Russia party should have received about 35%.
For many Russians, the Communists now seem more respected than Putin.
But they are no longer the same Communists.
They not only do not deny the pleasures of the worldly life, but party members are actually fond of wearing fur coats, traveling abroad, driving foreign cars, and using social media.
Some are millionaires — such as the charismatic agriculture chief Pavel Gruzdev (who was banned from participating in last month's election).
Although the party is still led by the 77-year-old Gennadiy Zyuganov, it is increasingly influenced and supported by younger members.
Take Nikolai Bondarenko as an example.
Thirty-six-year-old Bondarenko, nicknamed "Red Navalny," strongly criticized the poorly designed pension reform of 2018.
Not long ago, when a regional minister stated that Russians should be able to "eat better" on a meager monthly salary of 3,500 rubles (about $50), Bondarenko documented his efforts to prove the man wrong on his own YouTube channel.
Despite being threatened with a ban from running, Bondarenko was allowed to participate in the State Duma election last month.
Although he received support from Navalny's "smart voting" system, he still lost to the United Russia party's candidate.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently devised a title for a protest campaign accusing "the state and government" of taking over United Russia.
And then there is 43-year-old Anastasia Yudashova.
Like Bondarenko, she astonishingly lost the last election.
But she remains — and increasingly so — popular.
Thanks to the "smart voting" system, another rising star, the elegant Yekaterina Engalycheva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the Communist Party's modernization reflects a longing for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and although the country that realized these ideals was strict, it was not lacking in fairness and compassion.
In addition, like the liberal Navalny, today's Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision, under which an individual's whims do not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on this logic that all opponents of the Kremlin are increasingly uniting: forming a "United Russia" capable of confronting Putin.
This situation is not limited to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš — also known as the Czech Donald Trump — failed to be re-elected as prime minister, as the opposition coalition set aside their ideological differences and formed a common alliance, with its leader Petr Fiala likely to lead the new government alongside another opposition alliance.
As Fiala said, "People have had enough of populists," and they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also prepare a unified electoral list for the upcoming parliamentary elections and field a single candidate for prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still operates a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
Toppling Putin would be far more difficult, and it is not hard to predict that more comprehensive measures aimed at crushing the Communist Party will be introduced.
But the above practices also pose risks to the Kremlin.
The current situation is that the president claims Russian democracy "has not died," citing the presence of an "active opposition" as evidence, indicating that he is at least still interested in pretending that Russia has not been driven toward something nearly authoritarian.
Putin said he only wants stability.
But its regime is pushing Russia toward even more turbulent situations.
If the Kremlin were to set and implement rules as capriciously toward the Communist Party as it has toward the Russian liberals, thus driving the party underground, social explosion would be even more likely.
And if it decides to stop repressing, the Russian Communists — yes, the Communists — could become a force that cannot be ignored.
